article.headline: Charlotte 72, Fordham 66
article.story: CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- De'Angelo Alexander took 20 shots, but it wasn't enough for Charlotte coach Bobby Lutz. "I still think he passes up some shots he should take," Lutz said after Alexander scored a career-high 35 points in Charlotte's 72-68 win over Fordham on Saturday. "I want him to shoot it when he's open, because I know how good of a shooter he is." Alexander displayed that touch to start the second half, scoring 15 points in seven minutes. He hit two 3-pointers, had two driving layups, followed his own miss for a bucket in the lane and hit 3 of 4 free throws as Charlotte turned a two-point lead into a 44-37 advantage. The 49ers then slowly built the lead to 12 on E.J. Drayton's three-point play with 8 minutes left. Alexander, who was held to seven points in a win over Richmond Wednesday, made 6-of-9 3-pointers and grabbed 10 rebounds as he bested his previous career-high of 34 points set last season at St. Bonaventure. "He was incredible," Lutz said. "We tried to get him a shot as many times as we could." Drayton added 13 points and 10 rebounds and Leemire Goldwire also scored 13 for Charlotte (11-12, 5-6 Atlantic 10), which won its second straight game. Bryant Dunston had 19 points and eight rebounds Marcus Stout added 15 points on 6-of-15 shooting for Fordham (13-10, 6-5), which lost its third straight. The Rams, who made only 7-of-23 3-pointers, got within 66-63 on Stout's 3 with 31 seconds left. But Sebastian Greene was called for an intentional foul four seconds later and Leemire Goldwire then hit four straight free throws to put it away. The game marked the return to North Carolina for Fordham coach Dereck Whittenburg, who is best known in the state for throwing up the air ball that Lorenzo Charles caught and dunked at the buzzer to give North Carolina State the 1983 national championship. Whittenburg wasn't considered for the Wolfpack coaching job last summer, but said he has no ill feelings toward the school or current coach Sidney Lowe. "He was a teammate. I wished him well," Whittenburg said. "I knew they would beat (North) Carolina. I'm very proud of them. I'm in a wonderful situation here." The Rams got off to a good start, taking a 19-11 lead as Charlotte missed 16 of its first 20 shots. Alexander kept the 49ers in it by hitting 4 of 6 3-pointers in the first half as Charlotte rallied to take a 28-26 halftime lead despite 33 percent shooting. "I was very confident and I made some shots early," Alexander said. "I think I prepared myself better. I hadn't been playing as well of late. I just went back to the basics and I came away with a good game." Stout, Fordham's top scorer coming in at 15.1 points per game, was held to two points on 1-of-5 shooting in the first half as Charlotte used a variety of defenses to try to contain him. "They focused on him early on and he didn't get a lot of shots," Whittenburg said. "He had some wide-open shots, he just didn't make them. We struggled that way. "Our defense has been excellent. On the offensive end, when we have those open opportunities we have to take advantage of them."
